column31: In the design of User Interface (UI) and User Experience (UX), dark patterns refer to those user interfaces that are carefully designed to be deceptive or manipulative, misleading users to perform certain operations. For example, options such as unsubscribing or deleting an account are deliberately designed to be very inconspicuous and hard for users to find, while options like purchasing goods or subscribing to services are made very prominent to prompt users to consume. Their aim is often to make users complete actions that are beneficial to enterprises and the like against their own true intentions.

column35: I tried to delete the account of a short video platform. After entering the account settings, I did not see the obvious "delete account" option for a long time, only some general sections such as "privacy settings" and "account security".   Later, I searched for how to delete the account in the help center and followed the instructions, but I was asked to complete a series of complex authentication steps first, such as entering the mobile phone number and verification code at the time of registration, and answering some secret questions set at the beginning. But I can't remember some of the security issues, and it took a lot of effort to complete the verification.   Then various prompt boxes pop up to tell you what data will be lost after deleting the account, which can not be recovered, and so on, and you have to reconfirm whether you really want to delete it. The whole process is winding and unclear, and it takes a lot of time and energy to finally complete the account deletion operation.
